# Auto commit and push after completed tasks

When a task is fully completed (implementation done, build verified if applicable):

1. Run `git status` — if there are no changes, skip the rest.
2. Run `git add .`
3. Draft a concise, meaningful commit message focused on **why** (1–2 sentences).
4. Run `git commit` with that message.
5. Run `git push origin main`

Do not skip commit/push when there are file changes unless the user explicitly says not to in that message.

Use PowerShell-safe commit syntax on Windows (e.g. `git commit -m "title" -m "body"`), not bash heredocs.

Never use destructive git commands (force push, hard reset) unless explicitly requested.
